<div id="bookReviews">
  




  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section firstReview">
      

<div id="review_1371884810" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1371884810" />
    <a title="Ken Dennett" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/45621263-ken-dennett"><img alt="Ken Dennett" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1477652610p2/45621263.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1371884810?book_show_action=true">Aug 23, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ken Dennett" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ken Dennett" href="/user/show/45621263-ken-dennett">Ken Dennett</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1371884810" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14083980128590142971">This book hits the bull’s-eye from the first chapter: Chances are you don’t need to learn more about being happy; you need to apply what you already know. <br/><br/>That being said, though, Dr. George does lay out some helpful guidelines for doing this, such as practices for developing gratitude and recalibrating one’s brain away from a natural negativity bias. I’m also grateful for the practical tips on drafting a process plan that he outlines. <br/><br/>Every page has a reference to some profound piece of current</span>
  <span id="freeText14083980128590142971" style="display:none">This book hits the bull’s-eye from the first chapter: Chances are you don’t need to learn more about being happy; you need to apply what you already know. <br /><br />That being said, though, Dr. George does lay out some helpful guidelines for doing this, such as practices for developing gratitude and recalibrating one’s brain away from a natural negativity bias. I’m also grateful for the practical tips on drafting a process plan that he outlines. <br /><br />Every page has a reference to some profound piece of current research—and not just the most commonly cited studies we usually see. It ties together insights such as how visualizing one’s goals is related to the Reticular Activating System and the Pygmalion Effect, etc.<br /><br />Also, I wish all publishers would implement a requirement to do what Dr. George has done here: Each chapter closes with a bulleted list of practical takeaways. <br /><br />The chapter Fail, Fail Again, Fail Again Better by itself makes the book worth it. So many books on happiness focus on motivating you towards success, but rarely do they coach you through failure. He outlines very wise considerations about the best way to fail.<br /><br />Bottom line: If previous books and TED talks on success and happiness haven’t yielded the results you’re looking for, this book will help you remove the barriers that may be responsible. Highly recommended!</span>
  <a data-text-id="14083980128590142971" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


